<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,151,487]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,306,332]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName box="[448,656,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudapostata" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[448,656,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. pseudapostata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[667,726,306,332]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[667,726,306,332]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, from West Africa, are easily separated from 
<taxonomicName box="[1288,1429,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apostata">
<emphasis box="[1288,1429,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. apostata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from East Africa, by the lack of a pecten. There are some minor colour differences that may help differentiate females; 
<taxonomicName box="[261,403,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apostata">
<emphasis box="[261,403,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">D. apostata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a smaller apical wing spot and usually lacks any bright colour at the apex of the abdomen. This short series of specimens also suggests some sexual dimorphism with females having the wing crossband and the male not, and the male having more colour on the abdomen apex than the females.
</paragraph>
